# EPIZAP
Ferramenta computacional para predição de epítopos a partir de dados de Phage Display

## Requirements

### NEXTFLOW

This application was developed and tested on NEXTFLOW version 24.10.4;

-> Nextflow can be used on any POSIX-compatible system (Linux, macOS, etc), and on Windows through WSL. It requires Bash 3.2 (or later) and Java 17 (or later, up to 23). You can see which version you have using the following command:
java -version

More details on: https://www.nextflow.io/docs/latest/install.html

### DOCKER

https://docs.docker.com/get-started/

### Image from docker Hub

https://hub.docker.com/r/gianlucamajor/epizap

### Current version

docker pull gianlucamajor/epizap:v0.3.0-alpha

## Quick start

### Clone the repository

```
git clone https://github.com/gianlucamajor/epizap.git
cd epizap
```

### EPIZAP Smoke Test

The smoke test is a quick preliminary check that verifies whether the system's critical features are working.

For the smoke test we use a small set of DNA inserts that map to the kinetoplast DNA (kDNA) minicircles of T. cruzi.


So just run:

```
nextflow epizap.nf
```

These files are already included in the project and set as default parameters.

```
--reads dataSet/kDNA_gPhage/DNA_inserts_kDNA.fastq
--peptides dataSet/kDNA_gPhage/peptides_encoded_by_kDNA_inserts.fasta
--ref dataSet/kDNA_gPhage/y_strain_minicircles.fasta
--annotation dataSet/kDNA_gPhage/annotation_genomic_dummy.gff
--outdir results
```


Expected result:

Note: this is illustrative, not the exact output. The run id (e.g. `furious_engelbart`), revision hash, and per-task ids (e.g. `[f3/78af91]`) are randomly generated by Nextflow and will differ on every machine and every run.

```
