```

The output files should be in the `results` directory ( `--outdir results`), with one subdirectory per step:

```
results/
├── y_strain_minicircles-idx/
├── mapping/
├── max-score-mapping/
├── segments/
├── segments-annotated/
├── peptides-segment/
├── peptides-clustering-cc/
├── msa/
├── mview/
├── epitopes-by-msa-core/
├── graph/
├── graph-updated/
└── epitopes_report/
```

### EPIZAP output files

The `epitopes_report/` directory holds the final output of the pipeline:

- `*.fasta` — one record per predicted epitope (consensus sequence taken from the MSA of each connected component / GAGRS).
- `*.json` — one entry per predicted epitope, with: `ID`, `Epitope` (sequence), `Number of AGRs`, `Number of Peptides`, `Number of Inserts` (and the breakdown by group when `--inserts_group` is used), `MSA` (alignment page name), `Genomic Region Locus`, and `Features` (best proteome hit, genomic region annotation, and IEDB T. cruzi / human epitope hits, when those inputs are provided).
- `*.pickle` — the updated graph (Python pickle of the networkx graph object) used to generate the FASTA/JSON reports; can be reloaded for further analysis or to re-run `epitope_reporter.py` with different options (e.g. `--inserts-group`, `--iedb`).

## EPIZAP with pre-processed gPhage data (T. cruzi)

This example uses the pre-processed gPhage dataset (DNA inserts and encoded peptides from all patient groups, merged) mapped against the *T. cruzi* Brazil Clone A4 reference genome.

### gPhage data (download required)

The gPhage input files (`DNA_inserts_all_patients_groups.fastq`, `DNA_insert_IDs_by_group.tsv`, `peptides_encoded_by_DNA_inserts.fasta`/`.tsv`) are too large to ship in this repository. They are published on Zenodo (DOI [10.5281/zenodo.20854186](https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.20854186)) and described in detail in [dataSet/gPhage_data/README](dataSet/gPhage_data/README).

Download them, place the `.zip` files in `dataSet/gPhage_data/`, and unzip them there before running EPIZAP. You can do this manually or with the helper script:

```
bin/download_gphage_data.sh
```

It downloads each file from Zenodo into `dataSet/gPhage_data/`, verifies its MD5 checksum and unzips it.

### Reference genome (Br-A4, already in the repo)

The *T. cruzi* Brazil Clone A4 reference genome and annotation are already included in this repository as compressed files in `dataSet/genome_ref_Br_A4/` (see [dataSet/genome_ref_Br_A4/README](dataSet/genome_ref_Br_A4/README)). They also **need to be unzipped** before use:

```
unzip dataSet/genome_ref_Br_A4/t_cruzi_br_a4.fna.zip -d dataSet/genome_ref_Br_A4/
unzip dataSet/genome_ref_Br_A4/genomic.gff.zip -d dataSet/genome_ref_Br_A4/
```

### Run

```
nextflow epizap.nf \
  --reads dataSet/gPhage_data/DNA_inserts_all_patients_groups.fastq \
  --peptides dataSet/gPhage_data/peptides_encoded_by_DNA_inserts.fasta \
  --ref dataSet/genome_ref_Br_A4/t_cruzi_br_a4.fna \
  --annotation dataSet/genome_ref_Br_A4/genomic.gff \
  --inserts_group dataSet/gPhage_data/DNA_insert_IDs_by_group.tsv \
  --outdir results_gPhage_BrA4
```
